general.headline: Counsellor | Psychotherapist | Academic | Blogger
general.description:
I have centered my life goals around my passions of learning, helping and guiding others so that I will never work a day in my life! After the completion of my psychology degree in 2015, and my masters degree in counselling and applied psychotherapy at Jansen Newman Institute (Torrens University), I now look forward to undertaking my PhD one day within the near future.

My main interest is to conduct research into what drives human attraction besides physical attraction and personality/emotional attraction. As the two have the ability to continually change throughout one’s lifetime, this means that attraction is subject to change when one or both individuals change, either falling deeper in love or falling apart. My other interests include working with families helping and coaching them to work cohesively, working with students who are struggling academically, and conducting research on controversial issues in aim of raising awareness (articles which are accessible via LinkedIn). 

When working, I work on the premise that therapy should be an open dialogue between two individuals, understanding that people come from many different walks of life and different experiences. I believe that a collaborative and conversational oriented approach through a shared dialogue – like that of narrative therapy and/or Imago therapy is the best way to engage with my client’s presenting concerns. 

For more information about who I am and what I love doing, please feel free to email me on LinkedIn or my personal email: daniella.ghossein@outlook.com. I look forward to networking with you.

general.headline: Improving the impact of programs, policies, social innovation and social enterprise.
general.description:
Hi. Thanks for visiting my profile. Let me tell you a bit about myself.

My passion is working with change-makers and social entrepreneurs to improve the positive social and environmental impact of programs, policies, social innovation and social enterprise.

To achieve this, I founded Impact Evaluation.

The circuitous route to my niche traversed diverse roles and industries.

Community services:
I have Diplomas of Community Services Work and Employment Services. I have run a counselling service. I worked for several years with refugees. I coordinated a program to improve the health and wellbeing of children and young people. I have taught Diploma of Counselling, Diploma of Community Services Work (Mental Health and Alcohol and Other Drugs) and Graduate Diploma of Community Sector Management.

Training:
The only thing I love more than learning is imparting what I've learned. I have Cert IV in Training and Assessment. I’ve developed and delivered training in classroom, online and workplace settings.

Information systems:
I taught myself to program when I was 12. I’ve built web applications using PHP and ASP .NET (VB & C#). I’ve worked as a Data Analyst and a Web Developer.

Sustainability:
I have a Bachelor of Forest Science, Diploma of Sustainability and post-grad units in natural resource management. I coordinated campaigns that resulted in the protection of threatened ecosystems in Victoria and NSW.

Management:
I have a Diploma and Advanced Diploma of Management, Diploma of Business Administration, and Cert IV in Frontline Management. I’ve held management roles and taught Diploma of Project Management.

Areas of professional interest include social entrepreneurship, impact investing, shared value, collective impact, design thinking, B Corp, Results Based Accountability, data visualisation, systems theory, public policy, public health and community development.

Areas of personal interest include social change, history, philosophy, global politics and poetry.

jobs.description:
We work with Australian change-makers and social entrepreneurs to improve the positive social and environmental impact of programs, policies, social innovation and social enterprise. 

For each client, I assemble a small team with evaluation and relevant subject matter expertise. We develop an Evaluation Plan and Evaluation Framework, collect and analyse evidence, then make an assessment of the positive and negative environmental and social impact and make recommendations for how the program, policy, social innovation or social business model can be improved. As a follow-up engagement, we can develop and execute an Implementation Plan.

Most of our clients are in Melbourne, Geelong and south-west Victoria. To set up an initial informal meeting over coffee or on Skype, email cameron@impactevaluation.com.au.

I worked as a Data Analyst with the South West Primary Care Partnership (SWPCP). SWPCP is a voluntary alliance of community and health service agencies across South West Victoria. SWPCP works with member agencies and the community to identify, prioritise, and deliver evidence-based solutions that address complex health and wellbeing issues. My role was to review the evidence-base to advise on the development and selection of programs and to analyse and evaluate public health data and derive insights that inform health promotion and municipal public health and wellbeing planning.

I worked with SEED Consulting, a specialist team within Deakin University based in the School of Psychology and associated with the Strategic Research Centre for Social and Early Emotional Development (SEED). The Group provides consulting support to Deakin partners, with a strong focus on Prevention Science and providing high quality and informative evaluations and research support, aligned with the evidence base for healthy development across the lifespan from infancy to early adulthood.

SEED aims to promote a secure start to emotional life in all children and young people. We achieve this through original research on the developmental origins of mental health and disorder. We advise on the most effective approaches to promoting wellness and intervening at the earliest opportunities in troubled pathways. We bring together life-course, clinical and public health research and practice to describe the major milestones in emotional life. We then engage systems for translating our research knowledge broadly to the community, organisations and government.

Communities That Care Warrnambool aims to improve education attainment and the healthy development of children and young people and prevent antisocial behaviour and alcohol and drug use.

It works to prevent health and social problems by addressing the factors that increase the likelihood of positive development and decrease the likelihood of adverse outcomes for children and young people.

Brophy Family and Youth Services partnered with Communities That Care Ltd in a Department of Justice and Regulation funded project to deliver Communities that Care in Warrnambool.

general.headline: Wills & Estates Lawyer,  Principal at PB Ritz Lawyers
general.description:
I founded PB Ritz Lawyers in 2013.   We are a boutique wills & estates firm based in Sydney's CBD.

Our experience encompasses all things wills & estates, including:

- drafting complex wills with/without testamentary trusts and ancillary documents, such as enduring powers of attorney and appointment of enduring guardianship documents

- obtaining probate in common and solemn form, and grants for informal wills

- obtaining letters of administration with/without the will annexed

- facilitating the administration of complex estates

- drafting civil and administrative tribunal applications

- acting for plaintiffs and defendants in family provision claims and other will disputes.

I have prepared estate plans for clients with estates valued from $50,000 to $150,000,000 and everything in between.

I was the first solicitor in NSW to bring a claim under Part 4.4 of the Succession Act 2006 NSW which was disputed.  I was successful in obtaining a distribution order in favour of my client which took precedence over the general intestacy rules under Part 4.3 of the act.  See Re Estate Jerrard, deceased [2018] NSWSC 781

For excellence in wills & estates advice, or to have a chat with the wills & estates guru himself, give us a call.

general.headline: Barrister | Arbitrator | DRS Decision Maker | Board Director | Educator | Social Commentator
general.description:
Bridie is an experienced senior junior barrister with excellent all-round legal skills. She is able to carry matters from inception to completion, regardless of the direction the matter takes. She appears unled at both trial and appellate level, and in administrative tribunals and commissions of inquiry. She accepts instructions in all commercial, common law and public law disputes. Her broad practice traverses banking and finance, corporations law, contractual disputes, equity, trusts, trade practices, industrial, planning, communications, professional negligence, malpractice,  occupational discipline, insurance, marine insurance, insolvency, revenue, maritime, aviation, mining, energy, resources and utilities, construction, family law and crime.

Bridie is a sought after presenter, having presented extensively on topics including public law, corporations law, contracts, professional negligence, insurance and maritime law. 

Bridie practises in Domestic and International Commercial Arbitration. She is an accredited arbitrator, Fellow of CIArb and Fellow of ACICA. 

Prior to joining the profession, Bridie was an academic at two of Australia's leading universities, teaching international politics and international political economy, researching two theses on international currency and the politics of international currencies, and teaching Evidence, Litigation, Administrative Law and Professional Responsibility. 

Bridie can offer significant advantages to in-house counsel by assisting with advice, strategy, document preparation, submissions and appearances. The advantages include cost benefits and a direct relationship with a specialist advocate and advisor who appears regularly before courts and tribunals. Bridie is able to offer and agreed fee for legal work and a retainer for general advice work.

Bridie also serves and has served on a number of boards and is willing to expand her involvement in corporate governance.

jobs.description:
Jay Williams is a Barrister of the NSW Bar and High Court of Australia. Prior to coming
      to the Bar, Jay was a solicitor of the NSW Supreme Court and holds a Master of Law
      and Legal Practice, with a major in International Law at the University of Technology,
      Sydney and a Bachelor of Arts from the University of Melbourne with a major in Political
      Science and International Relations. With a primary focus on human rights law, Jay has
      been involved in several major public policy research projects and has been published
      
      by leading peer reviewed journals, including the International Journal of Human Rights.

jobs.jobTitle: Barrister  of the NSW Bar Association and practitioner of High Court of Australia
jobs.description:
General practice areas included:

(i) Public Law - constitutional and administrative law.
(ii) Criminal Law.
(iii) Civil Law.
(iv) Corporate and Commercial law
(v) Human rights Law.
(vi) Public international law.
(vii) Private international law 
(viii) indigenous law and Native Title.

•	S99 of 2014 v Minister for Immigration (Cth) & Ors, led by Ron Merkel QC in a Writ of Habeas Corpus on behalf of the 'Group of 356' detainees at the Manus Island RPC before the High Court of Australia

•	S156 v Minister for Immigration, - led by Mark Robinson SC in a challenge to constitutional validity of the Manus Island RPC before the High Court of Australia 

•	JHB & Ors v Secretary of Justice of the Republic of Nauru & Ors, led by Julian Burnside QC in a  Writ of Habeas Corpus on behalf of ten asylum seekers before the Supreme Court of Nauru

•	AG & Ors v Secretary of Justice of the Republic of Nauru led by Julian Burnside QC in a  Writ of Habeas Corpus on behalf of ten asylum seekers before the Supreme Court of Nauru

•	DPP v Lane – 2 month Murder Trial - Junior to Anne Healey - Supreme Court of NSW

•	R v Darren Robert Naden – Sentencing – Drug Misuse and Trafficking - Junior to Graham Turnbull SC – District Court of NSW

•	R v RSS - Appeal Against Conviction - Miscarriage of Justice - Junior to Chrissa Loukas SC - Court of Criminal Appeal NSW

•	R v Ryan, Appeal Against Sentence – Manifestly Excessive - Junior to Ian Barker QC - Court of Criminal Appeal NSW

•	Maloney v R - High Court - Racial discrimination – Civil Reading for Chris Ronalds SC whether the liquor restrictions contravened s 10 of the Racial Discrimination Act 1975 (Cth) or s 8 of the Racial Discrimination Act

•	Margan v Commonwealth Attorney General, Queensland Attorney General, NSW Attorney General – Sexual Discrimination - Junior to Kate Eastman SC - Federal Court of Australia - whether the failure to register same-sex marriages by various Federal and State Governments contravened the Sex Discrimination Act 1984 (Cth)

•	The Barngarla Native Title Claim – advice to lead counsel

From 2010-2011, Jay was appointed Research Coordinator of the Shadow Report on the Convention of the Rights of Persons with Disabilities. The Project Group is an umbrella group of the major disability groups in Australia who are working with DLA Phillips Fox on a pro bono basis to submit to the UN Disability Committee a Shadow Report on the Australian Government’s implementation of the Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities.

In 2009, Jay was invited by Associate Professor Karen Bubna-Litic to conduct legal research on a joint Canadian and Australian government grant examining the comparative impact of climate change on Indigenous people. The paper examines the devastating impact of climate change on Indigenous people and explores what legal rights exists for Indigenous people to seek redress.

jobs.jobTitle: Social Impact Study of the Uranium Mines on the Indigenous People of Kakadu National Park.
jobs.description: From 1997-2003, Jay spent five years in Arnhem Land studying and documenting traditional law, ceremony and culture of a remote Indigenous tribe. The title of the research is ‘The Endangered Cultures of Arnhem Land, The Bolmore Tribe.’ In short the work documents the ceremonial law, traditional culture, spirituality, language, hunting and gathering, medicine, story, song and art of the Bolmore Tribe. The work is of anthropological nature, which establishes the continuous and unbroken connection of the Bolmore Tribe to their traditional homelands. From here, the research raises important questions regarding native title, treaty, human rights and international law.

jobs.description:
Fraser is the Team Manager of the specialist legal recruitment team at Hays in Sydney. He focuses on in-house and private practice legal recruitment across a range of industries such as Professional Services, Construction, Property, Manufacturing, FMCG & Retail, Pharma, Engineering, Energy & Resources, Transport & Logistics, Security & Defence.

Prior to joining Hays Legal Fraser practised as a Solicitor for around 4 years with one of the UK's largest Criminal Defence firms, having been admitted as a Solicitor in the UK in 2011. Fraser pressed ahead to become one of the youngest Solicitors to obtain his 'Higher Rights of Audience'​ in England and Wales allowing him to further practice as a Higher Court Advocate at the Crown Court in 2013 onwards (work traditionally conducted by Barristers). Fraser's work typically saw him representing clients facing an extremely wide range of criminal offences; from murder and international drug supply to large scale banking fraud.

As a result, he is able to draw upon his legal knowledge and experience to understand his clients’ business needs and deliver quality service and results. Fraser is passionate about sourcing candidates who are the right technical and cultural fit to ensure a successful placement is made.

We’ve formed deep relationships with Australia’s key employers, from international legal practices to respected niche law firms and corporate, financial and public sector organisations. This enables us to offer a wide range of legal jobs across all levels of seniority, from paralegal jobs and newly qualified solicitor jobs to associate, partner and in-house legal and director jobs.

Fraser moved to the David Phillips and Partners' office in London where he conducted advocacy and provided expert advice to clients at all levels of criminal offending. Fraser gained a huge amount of experience in mitigation and trial defence work, appearing before the most senior Judges in the country. Fraser provided representation for one particular Defendant at the interview under caution stage and at early Court appearances for an extremely serious murder allegation. This particular matter became a high profile murder case heard before The Old Bailey Crown Court, and one that attracted a large amount of media attention. Fraser attended police stations, courts and prisons to provide professional legal service to a growing client base across the South of England.

Fraser was also heavily involved in providing advice in gang-land related offences ranging from Drug and serious violence, as well as professional 'white collar' criminal allegations.

Fraser then worked as a Higher Court Advocate in the Manchester and Lancashire region following his time spent down in the London Courts. Fraser was representing clients at all levels of criminal proceedings, with particular strength shown towards the more serious and complex cases heard before the Crown Court and Magistrates Courts. Fraser specialised in all areas of criminal law, advising clients and conducting advocacy for offences such as Drug Charges, Violence, Sexual Offences and high-end Fraud offences such as Banking fraud and theft from employee matters.

His vast wealth of expertise in criminal defence and serious fraud sectors materialised in him representing and advising on significant high profile cases with exceptional results.

jobs.companyName: Royal Australian Navy Reserve Legal Officer
jobs.description:
Track record as a Navy Legal Officer

Since 1993 I have conducted more than 100 trials by courts martial or Defence Force Magistrate for ADF members. I have successfully secured not guilty verdicts for ADF members in multiple serious complex trials, either at court martial, or before the Supreme and District Courts of NSW since 1993.

For instance, in 2014  I appeared as Defending Officer on behalf of one of the four Able Seamen ABMT accused who appeared before the longest running General Court Martial (GCM) in Australian history of 9 weeks (the HMAS NEWCASTLE GCM) for the alleged offences of sexual intercourse without consent, act of indecency, assault on a service ship, forcible confinement and prejudicial conduct. I secured acquittals for my client on all 5 charges after verdicts by direction were given to the GCM by the Judge Advocate on the primary counts of sexual intercourse without consent and act of indecency.

In 2015-2016 I appeared on behalf of a second  of the four accused from the HMAS NEWCASTLE GCM, who had his convictions quashed for the charges of act of indecency and forcible confinement  by the Defence Force Discipline Appeals Tribunal on 27 Mar 17 (Angre v. Chief of Navy (No.3) [2017] ADFDAT 2). 

The Tribunal held that his pleas of guilty on these charges were induced during a plea bargain by a misrepresentation by the prosecution that he would be sentenced by a Defence Force Magistrate rather than a GCM. The Tribunal held that "To hold  Able Seaman Angre to a plea of guilty entered on that basis, when he had no genuine consciousness of guilt , would be a grave miscarriage of justice."   

In 2016 I appeared as Prosecuting Officer on behalf of the DIrector of Military Prosecutions in a successful prosecution which was the longest running Restricted Court Martial (RCM) of 12 weeks in Australian history, in relation to allegations of unauthorized access to restricted data by an Army WO in the UAE.

jobs.description:
Mr Kossmann is an orthopaedic surgeon with almost 30 years of experience. Currently he practices in Melbourne and regional Victoria, operating at Knox Private Hospital and the Mildura Private Hospital. 

Mr Kossmann obtained his medical doctor (MD) degree at the University of Heidelberg.

He holds fellowships in general surgery, trauma surgery and orthopaedic surgery with training conducted in university hospitals in Germany and Switzerland.

Mr Kossmann is a fellow of the Royal Australasian College of Surgeons (FRACS) and a fellow of the Australian Orthopaedic Association (FAOrthoA).

As the Director, he founded the Department of Trauma Surgery at The Alfred hospital and expanded it to become one of the world-leading centres for trauma victims.

He was the founding Director of the National Trauma Research Institute (NTRI), an enterprise shared by The Alfred hospital and Monash University.

Mr Kossmann held professorships at the University of Zurich and Monash University and is currently a guest professor at the Antwerp University Hospital, Belgium where he teaches spinal surgery techniques on a regular basis.

Mr Kossmann has made a profound contribution to academia. In addition to teaching medical students and health professionals, he published 121 peer-reviewed articles and numerous book/chapters in the field of orthopaedic trauma and neurotrauma.

In 2010 Mr Kossmann completed a Master in Health & Medical Law at The University of Melbourne . In the same year, he founded Lex Medicus where he leads a world-class team of health professionals to deliver high quality medico-legal reports and impairment assessments across Australia and Europe. 

Contact me: tkossmann@lexmedicus.com.au or 03 9827 8093.

Entrepreneurship was always in her blood with Elyse’s family starting a promotional products business when she was just 12 years old. The school holidays saw her working for her parents.  

After completing a Business & Marketing degree at the University of Western Sydney and securing a job at an international company Elyse thought she had ‘made it’. However, she soon came to the realisation that she enjoyed the variety working in a small business offered and figured she might be suited to a smaller company where she would be able to offer her skills across a variety of areas in the business instead of specialising only in marketing. 

At 20 she joined the family business in promotional products full-time and while there learnt the importance of personalisation and the demand for custom products. She saw an opportunity to sell jackets that were designed by the customer and customised inside and out focusing on the leavers wear market and community groups. In August 2009 she took her first order of custom jackets and with that Exodus Wear was born. 

From there it was a quick transition to full-time entrepreneur but a long journey with many ups and downs to reach the point of running a multi-million dollar company servicing Australia wide. With highlights such as having Justin Bieber wear one of her jackets to learning first hand the pitfalls of sourcing direct from China every day the business teaches her something new. 

In 2017 she took her passion for video and create a YouTube Channel with weekly vlogs and how-to's and tutorials to help other people get started in video.

jobs.description:
Exodus Wear are one of the leading producers of leavers wear garments and custom dance tour jackets in Australia. 

What are leavers wear garments?

In Australia we have a tradition that when you go into your senior year of High School you get the privilege of being able to wear a jacket or jersey that is different to the standard school uniform. It is typically personalised with a nickname of your choice which many students spend hours deciding which name to pick. It is a big decision to a 17 year old as it will be on display for everyone to see for a whole year (we have seen a few crazy ones over the year and often have to refer to urbandictionary.com to decipher what some mean!)  

We ourselves had never heard of dance tours until we made our first dance tour jackets. We work with dance schools who are going overseas to perform or study typically at one of the major theme parks like Disneyland. 

We are constantly pushing the boundaries to make our jackets the most customisable on the market. We are famous for customising our jackets inside and out and in particular for our custom lining. The rule with our lining is that there is no rule! Whether you want to print your students names, a repeat pattern of your logo or even photos it is all possible. 

If you are unsure about how you would like your custom jacket to look our team can create designs for you and we even offer a free, no-obligation physical pre-production sample so that you can see your jacket in real life before placing an order. 

Our jackets are so popular they have been worn by Justin Bieber, Justice Crew, Kyle Sandilands, Stan Walker, Jedward, Israel Cruz and many more. Check out the photos below. 

With a current focus on expanding internationally to the USA, Hong Kong and New Zealand we are looking for Manufacturer's Representatives and Independent Sales Agents to represent us with current experience selling to High Schools, Sororities, Fraternities and the Dance industry.

Trained to identify, understand and interpret EU law issues.EU law is a dynamic, fast evolving and continuously expanding area of law, which impacts on a wide range of different areas of legal practice, such as employment law, family law, environment, planning, criminal law, immigration, competition, consumer law, intellectual property, social security and taxation. In addition to substantive rules, EU law imposes procedural obligations on national courts, state bodies and administrative authorities to ensure its effective implementation. It further provides mechanisms by which individuals and entities may seek redress for breaches. Following the entry into force of the Lisbon Treaty, the EU’s Charter of fundamental rights guarantees a wide-ranging set of rights, freedoms and principles and enumerates primary legal norms against which secondary EU legislation and national implementing measures may be interpreted, a lot of which most general practitioners do not appreciate.

general.headline: Founder and Head of Customer Success
general.description:
After practising law for several years I studied a post graduate degree in IT. This led to the development of www.cpdinteractive.com.au which provides online professional development for lawyers, including ethics, legal skills and practice management. After 20 years of delivering legal education I realised my number one love is education. This led to the development of VidVersity. As an educator I had been looking for an easy yet effective way to build online learning, that does not require a technical team, but rather me as an educator can develop myself. So after many years of research and development I together with Simon Quirk developed VidVersity.

In 2008, I started CPD Interactive. The core aim of this company was to drive quality, cost effective online professional development in Australia. It offers a broad suite of Continuing Professional Development and Continuing Legal Education training courses for lawyers for you and your firm to choose from. Clients include Herbert Smith Freehills, Lander & Rogers, Slater & Gordon, King Wood Mallesons and many more. in June 2018 CPD Interactive was acquired by The College of Law.

We also offer bespoke online training courses for all government and private sector clients with a focus on compliance and inductions.
 
I also been providing consulting services in the area of legal research to firms through Bliss Consulting since 1999. 

I am also a Legal Research Skills Adviser at Melbourne University Law School to both Masters and JD students. 


I also developed a legal research app called LawSauce, in partnership with Ruth Bird of Oxford University.

Specialties: Legal research, elearning, law, Professional Development for lawyers, instructional design, legal skills, conducting legal research.

Responsible for SEO & SEM activity, Lenovo's global website www.lenovo.com & social media to simplify the customers digital journey to grow both the Lenovo Brand & eCommerce business for PC's, Tablets, Smart Phones, Servers & Storage in over 120 countries.

A senior Talent Manager, Sourcing and Recruitment professional possessing proven specialist expertise and experience in business partnering, head hunting, development of recruitment strategies and employee engagement methodologies.

I offer a consultative and collaborative approach by business partnering across all business levels and leaders in pursuit of achieving organisational goals and objectives and adding value through a positive contribution to organisational growth, project delivery and culture development. 

I am highly experienced in specialist and technical based recruitment and have a genuine passion for candidate advocacy and innovation.

jobs.description:
nib is a leading health insurer with over 1.2 million customers in Australia and New Zealand. Established more than 60 years ago, nib is Australia's fourth largest and New Zealand's second largest health insurer. nib was the first health insurer to list on the ASX. With operations throughout Australia and New Zealand, nib has more than 1000 employees across the Group. Our success is underpinned by our organisational values- Value, Simplicity, People, Innovation, Choice and Excellence.

Attracting and sourcing the right people and establishing nib as the place to work is the core focus of my role. Working as part of the nib Group People & Development team, I play a key role in achieving nib's business strategy through establishing nib as an employer of choice in a variety of job markets locally and internationally through world class talent and attraction methodologies and innovative strategies to attract, develop, retain and pipeline top talent. 

Interested in joining our team? Feel free to contact me direct or alternatively you can view your next career opportunity at nib via www.careers.nib.com.au

UGL, a member of the CIMIC Group, possesses capabilities that extend across a broad range of services and whole-of-life solutions for diverse industries, utilising world leading, sustainable and innovative technologies. UGL partners with some of the world’s largest blue-chip companies and government agencies, private enterprise and public institutions.  
UGL’s skilled workforce, expertise in project management and end-to-end engineering, is backed by a continuous focus on safety, innovation and improvement.

Recruiting nationally across UGL's Rail and Defence business unit, my portfolio spanned across Engineering Services, Rail Freight and Passenger divisions along with supporting defence projects which service both the Australian Defence Force and the Commonwealth.
I was also the dedicated recruiter for the New Intercity Fleet $2.3 billion project, part of the RailConnect consortium.

TED believes passionately in the power of ideas to change attitudes, lives and, ultimately, the world.

Headquartered in Sydney, Australia, UGL operates worldwide across 52 countries employing 55,000 people with annual revenue approaching A$5 billion.

jobs.jobTitle: Global Head of Quality and Agile Practices
jobs.description:
This role has responsibilities for many parts of iflix business, my responsibilities will include but will not be limited to:

- Quality processes, manual, automated and as a state of mind
- Overseeing the implementation of automation frameworks
- Ensure Agile practises are followed within the teams
- Closing the gap between Customer Support and Tech and improving our collaboration
- Product Owner mentoring in regards to backlog management, story breakdown, etc.

I have worked with QA teams both here and in India. However I try to focus on building quality into all stages of the product development cycle . The QA teams I've worked with started off being post-development testing teams, focusing on regression testing applications built by teams prior to pushing code to production.

My goal has been to reduce the number of stand-alone QA's, not increase them. To embed good agile practices across the organisation and identify and eliminate any 'over the wall' behaviour the engineering teams have. If the organisation has a 'stand-alone' QA team, and a long post-engineering testing cycle, they are doing software WRONG!

QA as a standalone practise is actually a common sign of waste in software engineering, so eliminating waste should be every 'agile' teams goals. Agile teams need to consider 'quality' as building the thing right in the first place. This helps the team move on from separate 'checking' steps in their process. Quality is everyones responsibility, not just the testers.

If you lead a team of highly competent professionals who have the potential to become more influential and effective leaders and managers, I can help.

Are you satisfied you and your team are working at an optimum level?  Would you like proven tools to help you communicate better and achieve your desired outcomes faster?

Throughout my career I’ve taken charge of individuals and teams, enthusiastically guiding them through challenges. And now I work with individuals and organisations who genuinely want to improve and succeed, and need guidance to get there. 

MY APPROACH
As an engaging, effective and gifted communicator, I motivate leaders and teams and equip them with a set of skills and strategies for delivering best results. I deliver with impact and positively influence leadership success. With a warm and humorous approach my training programs consistently strengthen individuals and teams by giving them the courage and tools to have better conversations and achieve greater outcomes.

By showing you how to tap into your unique experiences and skills, improving communication both within and between departments, you’ll become more effective in the professional and personal roles you play.

general.headline: Graduate | Strategy | Deloitte Australia
general.description:
To combat the lack of pocket money from my parents, I would sell soft drinks out of my locker in high school with another high school business partner. At first, it was a few cans here and there, but the demand quickly grew and within a month, we had outfit our locker to ensure the cans remained cold using cooler packs taped to the inside walls. Selling 48 cans at $1 each per day, I was making about $150 profit a week. 

I discovered my flair for business and begun to sell lolly bags and chocolate coated marshmallows and strawberries, made in the high school kitchens. I even enlisted a business partner to help with the demand and sold them during lunch. 

Several months later, my school caught wind and shut me down for the selling of 'contraband' soft drinks and snacks with the PTA unhappy with the decrease in school canteen profits, but not before making over $2000 in profits.

In 2017, I graduated from the ANU with a double degree of Bachelor of Laws (Honours) / Bachelor of Science in Chemistry, and whilst I've put the soft-drink selling industry behind me, I'm looking to apply my problem solving skills to develop business strategy and tackle the issues posed by disruptive technologies. 

During my final year, I wrote my Law thesis on blockchain regulation and law reform to regulate the impact of blockchain on the Australian financial market, specifically examining the shift from the ASX's CHESS to Blockchain Clearing and Settlement and how Ch 7 of the Corporations Act should be reformed to accommodate this shift. 

Outside of my university studies, I am an avid travel photographer and have had photos published by various travel agents. I invest on the ASX recreationally and whilst at university, I wrote a weekly article for Woroni, the student newspaper, on weekly 'stock picks'. 

In my spare time,  I enjoy cooking (in particular baking and anything flour related), trail running and backseat coaching basketball and tennis from the comfort of my lounge room.

Brendan Chan is currently working within the financial services industry, and is committed to apply his proactive learning within a corporate environment by regularly adapting and seeking solutions to different challenges in his career. Brendan joined PwC Australia in 2015 as a Cadet, and is currently a Graduate as of 2018, responsible for providing Assurance to client's Financial Statement presentations and disclosures. He is also undergoing further studies to obtain a Chartered Accountants qualification. 

Prior to this role, Brendan joined A.S Watsons'​ Group in Hong Kong for 4 months as an Intern, and worked on Financial Controls and Systems and Financial Accounting. A.S Watsons'​ Group is the largest health and beauty retail group in Hong Kong, with over 12,000 stores in 33 markets worldwide serving over 27 million customers per week. It is majority owned by multinational conglomerate CK Hutchison Holdings Limited, as well as Singapore-government-owned Temasek Holdings. Brendan's responsibility ultimately incorporated an application of his retail-specific knowledge to analyse the risks, impacts and effectiveness of internal controls relating to multiple global business units across the Asia-Pacific Region.
 
Brendan graduated from UNSW in 2017 with a Bachelor of Commerce (Major in Accounting and Business Law), and was actively involved in co-curricular activities through ARC@UNSW's Volunteer Army Platoon, UNSW's Business School Career Mentoring Program, Investing For Charity and AUSFIC. Through these diversified experiences, Brendan continually strives to develop his business acumen, and insight within the corporate environment so as to become a successful consultant driving business performance and strategy in the near future.

schools.description: My PhD topic was focused on developing a design philosophy for learning systems to be persuasive in encouraging students to complete coursework. Students use a system called TTM (Task-Test-Monitor) that breaks down weekly tutorial tasks into bite-sized components, with matching multiple-choice tests for students to test their knowledge and understanding. The results showed that students desire guidance from a learning system and support from their instructors to flexibly fit around their busy schedules.I have published several aspects of my Ph.D. research, including in the prestigious Information & Management journal (ranked A* by the Australian Business Deans Council). I have also presented several papers at the Pacific Asia Conference on Information Systems and Australasian Conference on Information Systems (both ranked A by Excellence in Research for Australia).

My honours thesis was focused on measuring student acceptance of gamification in the learning environment. Gamification was a relatively new term to describe the process of making something more game-like, without creating a full game. The results showed that students were particularly positive towards gamification and hoped to see it applied in other courses they undertake.Aspects of my honours research were later published in the Journal of Information Systems Education (ranked B by the Australian Business Deans Council) and presented at the Pacific Asia Conference on Information Systems (ranked A by Excellence in Research for Australia).
Completed the undergraduate degree with a GPA of 3.5 and was awarded the Dimension Data "Top First Year Student" prize.

general.headline: Managing Partner, CMO @ PwC Australia | Telecom Specialist | Growth and Transformation Professional
general.description:
Mike McGrath is the Managing Partner of Clients & Markets at PwC Australia. With more than 25 years of industry experience, Mike has worked in the telecommunications, consulting and information technology sectors across the European, Asia-Pacific and North American markets.

Having commenced with PwC Australia in 2003, Mike was PwC’s National Consulting Markets Leader; was a member of the Consulting Leadership team; and, the Leader of the Growth Strategy Practice in Consulting. Mike is also PwC’s Client Leader Partner for Telstra, Australia’s leading telecommunications and information services company. Mike sits on PwC’s Global Telecommunications Leadership Team. His experience covers a wide range of industry sectors, including financial services, government, energy & utilities and transport & logistics.

Prior to his transition to PwC, Mike was a Vice-President at Bell Canada. He has led Consumer and Business P&L’s and has worked in the IT, strategy, networks, operations, product management and sales and marketing arenas.

A graduate of two Canadian Universities – Brock University (BA) and Queen’s University (MBA) – Mike also attained executive education qualifications from Stanford University; MIT (Massachusetts Institute of Technology); and, the University of Southern California.

Mike’s specialties lie in the areas of:
•	Telecommunications
•	Growth Strategies
•	Sales & Service Transformation
•	Channel Strategy
•	Marketing Strategy
•	Customer Insight
•	Customer Value Improvement
•	Customer Touch Point Analysis
•	Customer Retention
•	Stakeholder Engagement, Planning & Implementation

jobs.jobTitle: Executive Board Member/ Firm Leadership Team
jobs.description: Mike is also Executive Board Member – Firm Executive. In this role, Mike participates in PwC’s periodic meetings of the Firm Executive; contributes to the development and monitoring of the strategic plan; provides leadership to the organisation; identifies the firm’s goals and objectives; follows the Board’s code of ethics; and, is involved in ensuring financial controls and risk are managed effectively.

jobs.jobTitle: Partner, National Markets & Industries Leader – Consulting
jobs.description:
Mike was Partner, National Markets & Industries Leader – Consulting at PwC Australia
      for six years prior to taking his current role as Managing Partner. In this role, he was
      accountable for industry and services revenue growth, client experience and
      
      marketing.

As Growth Strategy Practice Leader, Mike was responsible for leading a practice that
      
      assisted clients in identifying and executing on market growth opportunities.

Mike was Board Director of the PwC Foundation – an entity comprised of PwC members who partner with charities to help build a more “cohesive” and “compassionate” community. The Foundation is committed to long-term, sustainable partnerships. As Board Director, Mike was an advisor to the Executive Director on the Foundation’s Strategic Plan; played a leadership role in the Foundation; assisted in maintaining fiscal responsibility; and, acted as an ambassador for the Foundation.

Mike was a former Vice-President of Bell Canada – Canada’s largest telecommunications company, providing telecommunications services to the consumer and small & medium business markets. As Vice-President, Mike was involved in the development and rollout of the company’s strategic vision. He also assessed the performance of other executives; evaluated the performance of Bell against its objectives; and, undertook organisational oversight.

Mike’s role at Bell also involved the Vice Presidency of Bell-Canada Enterprises (BCE).
      In this position, Mike was responsible for Strategy; Channel Management; Customer
      
      Account Management; Sales Transformation; Technology; IT; and, Operations.

schools.description: Mike is a graduate of Stanford University’s E-Commerce Strategy executive education program. A globally renowned institution, the university is located in Stanford, California (Silicon Valley). The Stanford Graduate School of Business provides executive education courses that arms senior executives with the knowledge and tools needed to deliver results at the top levels of management.

schools.schoolName: Massachusetts Institute of Technology - Sloan School of Management
schools.description: Mike completed an executive program with MIT Sloan in 2000. One of the world’s most prestigious universities in the world, MIT is located in Cambridge, Massachusetts. Offering courses in science, technology and additional disciplines, MIT’s Sloan School of Management delivers executive education programs that are specifically targeted to what executive leaders require in order to “drive innovation, lead change and solve complex business challenges.”

Mike undertook his MBA (Finance & Marketing) at Queen’s University, Canada. Established in 1841, Queen’s is located in Kingston, Ontario. The institution delivers a full range of educational disciplines and is highly regarded around the world for its quality education. Queen's is one of Canada's finest universities and the MBA program is ranked 1st in Canada and 4th outside of the United States by Business Week.

A Canadian University, Brock is located in Ontario. With a student population approaching 20,000, Brock University has been named as one of Canada’s top undergraduate research universities and has the highest employment rates amongst graduates of all universities in Ontario.
